body:
This is odd one, I can reproduce it only in test environment so it might be related to Rust test system(I also created separate [issue](https://github.com/chronotope/chrono/issues/391) in `chrono` project but not sure yet where this issue belongs to):

Some global state introduces random into  local `offset()`.
Normally with `TZ=Europe/Moscow` `Local.ymd(2000, 10, 29).and_hms(2, 0, 0)` has `+04:00` offset but when it's called within test context with *unused* `bug` variable it sometimes returns `+03:00` offset. 

It's easy to reproduce, create empty project, add `chrono` as depenedncy and create following test file:
```rust
use chrono::{ Local, TimeZone };

#[test]
fn t1() { test_bug(); }

#[test]
fn t2() { test_bug(); }

#[test]
fn t3() { test_bug(); }

#[test]
fn t4() { test_bug(); }

fn test_bug() {
    // If you remove this line then bug goes away.
    let bug = Local.ymd(2000, 11, 29).and_hms(2, 0, 0);

    let expected_time = Local.ymd(2000, 10, 29).and_hms(2, 0, 0);

    assert_eq!(expected_time.offset().to_string(), "+04:00");
}
```

And run it using following:
```bash
for n in {1..100}; do TZ=Europe/Moscow cargo test ; done
```

Expected:
Unused variable `bug` shouldn't affect anything.

Actual:
When `bug` variable is present random tests are failing. 

Setup:
- rustc 1.42.0-nightly (212b2c7da 2020-01-30) 
- rustc 1.42.0-nightly (859764425 2020-01-07)
- chrono 0.4.10
